questionTemplates.text:
M: Hello, Nancy. I'm sorry, but I just missed the 8:50 bus to the museum. I'm afraid I'll be a little late.
W: It doesn't matter. The next bus will be coming at 9:00. You can catch that one. The museum opens at 9:30.
{a}

W: Mrs. Long's briefing seems to go on forever. I was barely able to stay awake.
M: How could you sleep through that? It was very important for the mission we were going to carry out.
{a}

M: Did you mind coming back by coach instead of by train?
W: No, we didn't mind at all. It took a lot longer, but it was very comfortableand it was much cheaper.
{a}

W: Where're Linda's pencils? I can't find them.
M: Oh, really? I think they're in her pencil-box.
{a}

M: Do you know the guy with the glasses? He talks too much.
W: Don't you remember him? He was always with that terrible girl from school.
{a}

M: Do you like your new house?
W: It's nice to have enough space for all my things, so I'm glad to move in. But I miss my old friends and neighbors. I especially miss living close to the school.
{a}

M: Jack has got a bad cold. Could you get some medicine for him?
W: OK, I'll go to the supermarket right now.
{a}

W: Why don't you give up drinking? It's such a bad example to the children.
M: It's one of the pleasures in my life. That's why.
{a}

M: May I help you?
W: Yes, I'd like to buy a swimming suit for my elder sister as a birthday present.
{a}

W: Poor Smith, your marriage hasn't exactly been roses, has it?
M: Not exactly, married to a woman who overdoes it. I mean, after all when you've been mar-tied ten years, you don't expect a woman to sit on your lap for two hours every evening, call you at work twelve times a day and talk baby talk.
{a}

W: Well, you have cleaned out the refrigerator this time. Nothing is left.
M: Oh, yes. I had a lot of work all day and I had only a small lunch at the office.
{a}

M: Why is Susan looking upset?
W: I had her play piano instead of going out to play.
{a}

W: Do you have a pen friend?
M: Yes, she is a Canadian.
{a}

W: How do you like the dishes in our restaurant?
M: Oh, they are wonderful. It's quite some time since I have enjoyed myself so much. And your service is perfect, too.
{a}

W: Congratulations,Tom. I heard you got a job with the Wilson Company.
M: Thanks, Professor Black, but it's a little too soon for congratulation, all I got so far is an interview, early next week, on Thursday.
{a}

W: I was hoping that we could see Jerry here today.
M: He was planning to come, but then his wife's father fell down some stairs and they had to take him to a doctor.
{a}

W: Hello, I'm Mary, but have we met before?
M: No, I'm new here. I just started working for this company.
{a}

M: When I have succeeded, I'll hold a party for all my friends.
W: Never forget your promise!
{a}

M: I thought that computer cost 1,000 dollars.
W: It used to, but the shop owner has lowered the price by 150 dollars.
{a}

M: Have you finished reading SUPER HERO?
W: Yes I enjoyed every page of it. It's so exciting.
{a}

W: Do you have the seminar schedule with you? I'd like to find out the topic for Friday.
M: I gave it to my friend, but there should be copies available in the library. I can pick one up for you.
{a}

M: You know, I'm just not too sure if the new salary will be high enough or even the new position is really what I want. Besides, I like the work that I am doing now.
W: It sounds as though you've already made up your mind about what you are going to do.
{a}

W: I'm going to take down those curtains and put up new ones.
M: Why? What's wrong with them?
{a}

W: How many more chairs should we get for the meeting?
M: Don't we have enough by now?
{a}
